Then, a function is defined to remove both punctuation and stopwords in sentences.

In [ ]:
def text_cleaning(text):
        punc_removed=[char for char in text if char not in string.punctuation]
        punc_removed_join = "".join(punc_removed)
        punc_removed_join_clean = [word for word in punc_removed_join.split() if word.lower() not in stopwords.words('english')]
        return punc_removed_join_clean

After that, I test the defined function by applying it into column of verified reviews in amazon_review_df dataframe. Then I compare between the original reviews and the clean ones after removing punctuations and stopwords.

4. Test AI/ML Models¶

The dataset was first split into train and test dataset. 80% of the data was used for trainining and the performance was asssed on remaining 20%.

In [ ]:
X.shape
Y.shape

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
X_train, X_test,  Y_train, Y_test =train_test_split(X, Y, test_size = 0.2)

Now let's fit the model with the train dataset and predict the test set result by using 3 different methods: Naive Bayes, Logistic Regression and Gradient Boosting Classifier. The heatmap was constructed to visualize the confusion matrix and the classification_report () function from the sklearn library was used to generate the precision metric

In [ ]:
from sklearn.naive_bayes import MultinomialNB
NB_model = MultinomialNB()
NB_model.fit(X_train, Y_train)
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, confusion_matrix

Y_predict_test_1= NB_model.predict(X_test)
conf_matrix_1= confusion_matrix(Y_test, Y_predict_test_1)

sns.heatmap(conf_matrix_1, annot= True)
print(classification_report(Y_test, Y_predict_test_1))

              precision    recall  f1-score   support

           0       0.62      0.32      0.42        57
           1       0.94      0.98      0.96       573

    accuracy                           0.92       630
   macro avg       0.78      0.65      0.69       630
weighted avg       0.91      0.92      0.91       630

The confusion matrix above was used to evaluate the performance of the Naive Bayes classification method. With the Naive Bayes, there are 18 and 560 reviews are classified correctly while 39 are false negative (type II error) and 11 are false positive (type I error). Additionally, the classification report shows the percentage of correct positive predictions relative to total positive predictions at 0.91. Now, let's apply another model to see which is the best classification method

In [ ]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
LR_model = LogisticRegression()
LR_model.fit(X_train, Y_train)

Y_predict_2= LR_model.predict(X_test)
conf_matrix_2 = confusion_matrix(Y_predict_2, Y_test)

sns.heatmap(conf_matrix_2,annot = True)
print(classification_report(Y_test, Y_predict_2))

              precision    recall  f1-score   support

           0       0.79      0.26      0.39        57
           1       0.93      0.99      0.96       573

    accuracy                           0.93       630
   macro avg       0.86      0.63      0.68       630
weighted avg       0.92      0.93      0.91       630

The Logistic Regression model is tested next and the confusion matrix shows that 15 and 570 reviews are correctly classified whereas 42 and 4 reviews are false positive and false negative respectively, with precision weighted average at 0.92, slightly higher than that of Naive Bayes method.

Gradient Boosting Classification method's performance seems quite similar to Naive Bayes with the weighted average of precision also reaches 0.91.The confusion matrix constructed from this method shows that 5 and 570 reviews are correctly classified higher that of Naive Bayes method and the total number of falsely classified reviews is smaller indicating slightly better performance. In conclusion, the Logistic Regression model performs the most precised classification among the 3 methods used with higher precision percentage.
